{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011GiJTKwtMf38BLdkzjwxEX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: schema-migration-safety\n     3→description: Plan and apply backwards-compatible two-step schema changes for Django migrations without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Schema Migration Safety (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill for model field changes that need rollout-safe migrations.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `app_label`\n    13→- `model_name`\n    14→- `field_name`\n    15→- `field_type`\n    16→- `add_field_kwargs`\n    17→- `final_field_kwargs`\n    18→- `previous_migration`\n    19→- `add_migration_name`\n    20→- `finalize_migration_name`\n    21→- `backfill_value`\n    22→\n    23→## Execution Checklist\n    24→\n    25→1. Add the new model field in a safe first state (nullable or with safe default).\n    26→2. Create migration 1 to add the field and backfill existing rows.\n    27→3. Create migration 2 to enforce the final constraint shape.\n    28→4. Keep changes narrow: no unrelated refactors.\n    29→5. Verify migration dependency chain is linear and explicit.\n    30→\n    31→## Guardrails\n    32→\n    33→- Avoid one-shot `NOT NULL` additions on large existing tables.\n    34→- Avoid data backfill in request-time code paths.\n    35→- Keep backfill logic idempotent.\n    36→- Preserve reversibility with clear migration operations.\n    37→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"740c8e4f-41a4-4b8c-86d6-6927ef1c9e13","uuid":"a9d6c459-d61a-4465-8d9a-bf643877ee2d"}
